In July and August 2004, devastating floods in Bangladesh claimed over 700 lives and submerged 38% of the country, displacing millions.
The Brahmaputra River surged dangerously, prompting evacuations and relief efforts.
Monsoon rains and melting snow from the Himalayas exacerbated the crisis, affecting India, Bangladesh, and Nepal.
The situation remains dire, with millions displaced, villages inundated, and fatalities rising.
The government and international organizations are mobilizing aid to assist those affected, as the floodwaters continue to wreak havoc across the region.
